Sunday August 25th 2013 5:55 pm -04:00,What happens in Python is that an assignment statement like area = base * height assigns the evaluation of the expression base * height to the area variable so if you later in the code change the values that variables base and height refer to you just changed the memory address in those two variables (they will now point to the new values). If you want to change area youd have to recompute it using the new base and height values.I wouldnt say this is counter-intuitive but it is Pythons way of doing things. A way of avoiding this is to define a function to calculate the area with the base and height params. That way each time you call the function you will pass arguments to it and get a result., Unresolved,2
