Monday August 26th 2013 10:08 am -04:00,Yes this is the beauty of Python. Its part of the philosophy of the language! This is a quote from the Wikipedia article about the Python programming language:***begin quote***The core philosophy of the language is summarized by the document PEP 20 (The Zen of Python) which includes aphorisms such as:[32]Beautiful is better than ugly.Explicit is better than implicit.Simple is better than complex.Complex is better than complicated.Readability counts.Rather than requiring all desired functionality to be built into the languages core Python was designed to be highly extensible. Python can also be embedded in existing applications that need a programmable interface. This design of a small core language with a large standard library and an easily extensible interpreter was intended by Van Rossum from the very start because of his frustrations with ABC (which espoused the opposite mindset).[19]While offering choice in coding methodology the Python philosophy rejects exuberant syntax such as in Perl in favor of a sparser less-cluttered grammar. As Alex Martelli put it: To describe something as clever is not considered a compliment in the Python culture.[33] Pythons philosophy rejects the Perl there is more than one way to do it approach to language design in favor of there should be one—and preferably only one—obvious way to do it.[32]***end quote***PS: I ended up buying the book and I find it great. I give my thanks to the authors for not only devoting their time to this course but for writing a great book that Im sure will help lots of people to program in Python!, Resolved,0
