Thursday August 29th 2013 10:35 am -04:00,Because you cant store the value of a print statement in a variable so you cant really do something like return = sum(1 3) unless the sum() function returns a value. Check this code out:>>> def add(num1 num2):	print(num1 + num2)	>>> add(1 3)4>>> result = add(1 3)4>>> result>>> As you can see if you assign the variable result a function call add(1 3) you will get a printed result on the screen but when you call the result variable to see the value its referring to you dont get anything back because its a None type.Also remember that sum() is a built-in function. Dont use names of built-ins for your own function declarations!Hope this helps., Unresolved,3
